C.2.5Â Â Interpreting binary files with complex headers



Some binary files are headerless (also called raw files), i.e., they do not contain any extra information in a header, just the data (for example, the samples of a signal). However, most binary files start with a header. If the header information is encoded in the same format as the data itself, it is relatively easy to inspect the file contents using a software such as FileViewer. However, if the header is composed by a mix of float, short, char variables, etc., then the interpretation is trickier.



As an example, assume the file floatsamples.bin generated with ListingÂ C.1. FigureÂ C.5 shows the floatsamples.bin file contents interpreted as hexadecimal bytes.








FigureÂ C.5: Contents in hexadecimal of file floatsamples.bin generated with ListingÂ C.1.





The data is in float format but the header is a 2-bytes short. Hence, reading the file as float will get all numbers wrong as shown in FigureÂ C.6. The correct would be to skip the header and then read the data.








FigureÂ C.6: Interpretation as big-endian floats of file floatsamples.bin generated with ListingÂ C.1. The numbers are wrong (the data after the header is  âˆ’ 2,âˆ’1,0,1,2) because the reading is not aligned with the end of the 2-bytes header.





The companion code laps_dump.c can be helpful in situations where the header is heterogeneous. One can study its source code to understand how to simultaneously visualize all interpretations (short, float, etc.). For example, the interpretation of the big-endian file floatsamples.bin generated with ListingÂ C.1, which is not trivial on a little-endian PC, can be performed as follows.



Recall that the useful information is the sequence 5,âˆ’2.0,âˆ’1.0,0.0,1.0,2.0. The commandlaps_dump.exe floatsamples.bin swapprovides the output below. Each line indicates distinct interpretations (char, short, etc.) assuming the element starts at the corresponding byte. For example, the second line below indicates that the corresponding byte is 5, its ASCII code (fourth column) is a special character, and the fifth column interprets this byte as the beginning of a short variable composed by the pair of bytes 0x05C0, which corresponds to 1472 in decimal. Note that the numbers of interest in this case are inside frame boxes. The file size is 22 bytes, but after reading 16 bytes, the code tries to read the next double (8 bytes) and aborts the execution because there are only 6 bytes remaining. This is the reason for not observing the last element 2.0. Typically the last bytes will be missed.



